its of 2004 (U.S.)]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Youtube|GxBSyx85Kp8|Yeah! (Music video)}}\n*{{MetroLyrics song|usher|yeah}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Usher singles}}\n{{Ludacris singles}}\n{{Lil Jon}}\n{{Billboard Year-End number one singles 2000\u20132019}}\n\n[[Category:2004 singles]]\n[[Category:Usher (musician) songs]]\n[[Category:Lil Jon songs]]\n[[Category:Ludacris songs]]\n[[Category:Tego Calder\u00f3n songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs) number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Canadian Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:European Hot 100 Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Dutch Top 40 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Single Top 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Rap/Sung Collaboration]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Australia]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Austria]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Denmark]]\n[[Category:SNEP Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Germany]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Norway]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:UK R&B Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Ultratop 50 Singles (Wallonia) number-one singles]]\n[[Category:MTV Video Music Award for Best Male Video]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Director X]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Sean Garrett]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ludacris]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Lil Jon]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Lil Jon]]\n[[Category:Songs written by LRoc]]\n[[Category:Arista Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Usher (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Patrick \"J. Que\" Smith]]\n[[Category:2004 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about betrayal]]\n[[Category:Songs about sexuality]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2004 single by Usher}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       =\n| cover      = Usher-yeah.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Usher (musician)|Usher]] featuring [[Lil Jon]] and [[Ludacris]]\n| album      = [[Confessions (Usher album)|Confessions]]\n| B-side     = {{hlist|\"Red Light\"|\"Sweet Lies\"}}\n| released   = {{start date|2004|01|27}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single]]|[[Music download|digital download]]|[[maxi single]]}}\n| recorded   = {{start date|2003}}\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Hip hop]]|[[crunk&B]]}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=4|s=10}}\n| label      = [[Arista Records|Arista]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Christopher Bridges]]|[[LRoc|James Phillips]]|[[Lil Jon|Jonathan Smith]]|LaMarquis Jefferson|[[Patrick M. Smith|Patrick Smith]]|[[Sean Garrett]]}}\n| producer   = [[Lil Jon]]\n| chronology = [[Usher (musician)|Usher]]\n| prev_title = Can U Help Me\n| prev_year  = 2002\n| next_title = [[Burn (Usher song)|Burn]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Lil Jon]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = [[Salt Shaker (song)|Salt Shaker]]\n | prev_year  = 2003\n | title      = Yeah!\n | year       = 2004\n | next_title = [[What U Gon' Do]]\n | next_year  = 2004\n}}\n{{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Ludacris]]\n | type       = singles\n | prev_title = [[Blow It Out (Ludacris song)|Blow It Out]]\n | prev_year  = 2003\n | title      = Yeah!\n | year       = 2004\n | next_title = [[Lovers and Friends (song)|Lovers and Friends]]\n | next_year  = 2004\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Yeah!'''\" is a song by American singer [[Usher (musician)|Usher]]. The song is co-written by [[Sean Garrett]], [[Patrick J. Que Smith]], Robert McDowell, [[LRoc]], [[Ludacris]], and [[Lil Jon]], who also produced the song. It also features guest vocals from Lil Jon and Ludacris, with the former also producing the song as well as incorporating [[crunk]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\u2014which he coined as [[crunk&B]]\u2014in the song's production. The song was released as the [[lead single]] from Usher's fourth studio album ''[[Confessions (Usher album)|Confessions]]'' (2004) on January 27, 2004, after Usher was told by [[Arista Records]], his label at the time, to record more tracks for the album.\n\n\"Yeah!\" topped the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart for 12 consecutive weeks, before being dethroned by Usher's follow-up single \"[[Burn (Usher song)|Burn]]\". \"Yeah!\" was the longest-running number one single in 2004,<ref>[[List of Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles of 2004]]</ref> subsequently topping the year-end chart on the Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web |title=Top 100 Songs of 2004 - Billboard Year End Charts |url=http://www.bobborst.com/popculture/top-100-songs-of-the-year/?year=2004 |website=Bobborst |accessdate=22 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109225505/http://www.bobborst.com/popculture/top-100-songs-of-the-year/?year=2004 |archive-date=November 9, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). The song received a similar response in other countries, topping in other twelve charts worldwide. It was certified platinum in several countries, including [[Australian Recording Industry Association|Australia]], [[Ultratop 50|Belgium]], [[Canadian Hot 100|Canada]], [[Media Control Charts|Germany]] and [[VG-lista|Norway]], and received a two times platinum certification in [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|New Zealand]]. The song peaked in the top-ten in several Year-end charts.\n\nAn accompanying music video, directed by [[Director X|Mr. X]], shows Usher, Ludacris and Lil Jon performing choreography in a club in front of blue laser beams. \"Yeah!\" won a [[Grammy Award for Best Rap/Sung Collaboration|Best Rap/Sung Collaboration]] at the [[47th Grammy Awards]], while being nominated for [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]]. The song ranked second on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 2000\u20132009 Decade-end chart. As of September 2013, the song has sold over 4 million copies in the US.\n\n==Background and release==\nIn the fall of 2003, Usher submitted his fourth studio album, ''[[Confessions (Usher album)|Confessions]]'' (2004), to his record label [[Arista Records]]. However, when the singer and the company's then-president [[L.A. Reid]] listened to the songs, Reid felt the album lacked a song that had the potential to be released as the album's [[lead single]]. In light of this, Usher was told to record a few more tracks, and so he enlisted American rapper-producer [[Lil Jon]] to aid in musical production.<ref name=\"ReidShook\">{{Cite news |last=Reid |first=Shaheem |title=The Road To Confessions: How Usher 'Shook A Million' |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1486094/20040331/usher.jhtml |publisher=[[MTV News]]. [[Viacom Media Networks]]|date=March 31, 2004 |accessdate=March 2, 2008}}</ref> Lil Jon recalled, \"He [Usher] needed a single. They had 'Burn', 'Burn' was hot, but they needed that first powerful monster. That's when I came in.\"<ref name=\"ReidKingMe\">{{Cite news|last= Reid |first=Shaheem |title=Usher: King Me \u2013 Part 3 |url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/u/usher/news_feature_052404/index3.jhtml |publisher= MTV News. Viacom Media Networks |accessdate= March 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080119122454/http://www.mtv.com/bands/u/usher/news_feature_052404/index3.jhtml |archivedate=January 19, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nSeveral months prior to Lil Jon's involvement in the production of ''Confessions'', he was commissioned by [[Jive Records]] to produce fifteen tracks for rapper [[Mystikal]]. The rapper would only select two tracks, which provided Lil Jon the opportunity to give leftover songs to other record labels. Without Lil Jon's knowledge, Jive Records gave one of the leftover tracks to [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] artist [[Petey Pablo]] which would eventually become \"[[Freak-a-Leek]]\". However, Lil Jon, assuming that the song had not been used, gave the production to Usher, resulting in a rough version of \"Yeah!\". Eventually realizing the mistake after Pablo played \"Freek-a-leek\" to Lil Jon, the latter insisted on producing more tracks for Pablo; however, Pablo did not give up the song, due to the fact that it was already recorded and had been getting responses from Southern radio. Lil Jon commented, \"With so much invested, Jive wouldn't give up the cut.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,634074,00.html|title=''Yeah'', Lil Jon came through again |last=Drumming|first= Neil|date=May 14, 2004|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]| publisher=[[Time Warner]]|accessdate= November 23, 2008}}</ref> Lil Jon jumped back in the studio and created an equally catchy replacement track.<ref name=\"ReidKingMe\"/> Though \"Yeah!\" was now completed, the label still had \"Burn\" on queue for the lead single. Usher's friend and former [[A&R]] rep Kawan \"KP\" Prather commented: \"'Burn' being a great song is one thing, but it's one of them things where people said, 'It's strong, but can we make history with that?' At the end of the day, you want an event.\" Usher was still unsure if \"Yeah!\" was the right choice.<ref name= \"ReidRoad\">{{Cite news |last=Reid |first= Shaheem |title=Road To The Grammys: The Making Of Usher's Confessions |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1496656/20050207/usher.jhtml |publisher= MTV News. Viacom Media Networks|date= February 7, 2005 |accessdate=March 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\nLil Jon, who is also a DJ, then decided to leak the record to DJs across the country after the record companies shut down for Christmas break. By the time they got back to business in January, the record already had thousands of radio plays with no label involvement. Usher still opted to go with \"Burn\" as the lead single as a music video was already planned,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Reid |first=Shaheem |title=Usher To Share His Confessions In March |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1483836/20031219/usher.jhtml |publisher= MTV News. Viacom Media Networks|date=February 7, 2005 |accessdate=March 2, 2008}}</ref> however, the responses to \"Yeah!\" were overwhelmingly favorable,<ref name=\"ReidRoad\"/> and \"Yeah!\" was released as the first single with \"Burn\" becoming the second single from the album. The single was released in the United States on January 27, 2004 as a CD single and [[12-inch single|12\" single]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Yeah &#91;US 12\"&#93; |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/yeah-us-12-quot--mw0000419503|publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=August 12, 2012}}</ref> [[LaFace Records]] sent \"Yeah!\" to US [[contemporary hit radio]] on February 7, 2004.<ref>http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=November 1, 2005&Format=1 {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231060403/http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=01%2F11%2F2005&Format=1 |date= December 31, 2014 }}</ref> In the United Kingdom, it was released as a CD single, containing the album and instrumental version of the song, and two additional tracks from the album, \"Red Light\" (also produced by Lil Jon) and \"Sweet Lies\".<ref name=\"UK1\"/><ref name=\"UK2\"/>\n\n==Composition and reception==\n{{Listen|filename=Usher Yeah.ogg|title=\"Yeah!\"|pos=right|description=\"Yeah!\" uses elements of [[crunk]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], which song producer [[Lil Jon]] coined as [[Crunk&B]].<ref name=\"Shepherd\">{{cite web |last=Shepherd |first=Julianne |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1538791/soul-bounce-crunk-n-b-101.jhtml|title=Soul Bounce: Crunk 'n' B 101|publisher=MTV News. Viacom Media Networks|date=August 18, 2006|accessdate=August 12, 2012}}</ref>|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\"Yeah!\" combines the genres of [[crunk]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] genres, to form [[Crunk&B]], which [[Lil Jon]] described as \"R&B songs that get you crunk, make you wanna wild out\".<ref name=\"Shepherd\"/> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'s}} Jem Aswad found the song to contain crunk and transition between [[Hip hop music|hip hop]], [[Soul music|soul]] and ballad genres.<ref name=\"Aswad\"/> The song was co-written by [[Sean Garrett]], [[Patrick J. Que Smith]], [[Ludacris]], Robert McDowell, and [[LRoc|James Elbert \"LRoc\" Phillips]]. According to the sheet music published at Musicnotes.com by [[Sony/ATV Music Publishing]], \"Yeah!\" is written in [[common time]] with a moderately slow tempo of 105 beats per minute, It is written in the key of [[G minor]]. Usher's vocal range spans from the low note of B{{music|flat}}<sub>3</sub> to the high note of B{{music|flat}}<sub>4</sub>.<ref>{{cite web|title=Usher \u2013 Yeah! |publisher=Musicnotes.com. [[Sony/ATV Music Publishing]]}}</ref>\n{{Quote box|quoted=true|bgcolor=#ffeeaa|align=left|width=30%|salign=left|quote= \"Yeah!\" was an uncomplicated song about flirting with girls in a night club; it left plenty of air-conditioned space for Usher to coo and for the producer Lil Jon to bark the interjections [...] The lyrics were delivered like flashes of light: brief, anxious, and exciting, and perfectly suited to a voice that is long on control and short on texture.|source=\u2014[[Sasha Frere-Jones]] of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' on its success.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2008/06/02/usher-2-0 |title=USHER 2.0 |website=[[The New Yorker]]|accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref>}}\n\"Yeah!\" was lauded by contemporary critics for its production. Jem Aswad of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' called it \"irresistibly crunked-out\", adding, \"the ensuing track glides smoothly between club-friendly hip-hop soul and ballads.\"<ref name=\"Aswad\">{{cite web |last=Aswad |first=Jem |title=Confessions (2004): Usher |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,602386,00.html |work=Entertainment Weekly |publisher=Time Warner|date=March 26, 2004 |accessdate=March 2, 2008}}</ref> Laura Sinagra of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' commented that the song \"creates sensual panic by combining Usher's jumpy attacks with Jon's sublime, frayed beats.\"<ref name=\"Sinagra\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/usher/albums/album/5165180/review/5944284/confessions|title=Usher: Confessions : Music Reviews|last=Sinagra|first=Laura|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=March 24, 2004|accessdate=May 7, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071002015448/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/usher/albums/album/5165180/review/5944284/confessions|archivedate=October 2, 2007}}</ref> Jon Caramanica of ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' noted that \"Yeah!\" is the first song to mix \"mainstream R&B and menacing Southern crunk.\"<ref name=\"Caramanica\">{{cite journal|last=Caramanica|first=Jon|date=April 2004|title=Review: ''Confessions''|journal=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|publisher=Alpha Media Group|page=132}}</ref> Sal Cinquemani of [[Slant Magazine]] said that the song has brought Usher to a \"whole new level of crunk.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Sal Cinquemani |first=Sal |title=Usher: Confessions |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/music_review.asp?ID=431 |magazine=[[Slant Magazine]] |year=2004 |accessdate=March 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316222807/http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/music_review.asp?ID=431 |archivedate=March 16, 2008 }}</ref> Andy Kellman of [[Allmusic]] described the song as a \"crunk-meets-R&B foundation\" which features an \"instantly addictive eight-note keyboard vamp\".<ref name=\"Kellman\">{{cite web |last=Kellman |first=Andy |title=Confessions: Usher |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r681098|pure_url=yes}}|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=March 3, 2008}}</ref> He added that the song is \"so absorbing that Ludacris' 1500th guest verse floats by with little notice.\"<ref name=\"Kellman\"/> Matt Cibula of [[PopMatters]] characterized the song as a \"full-fledged club \u00fcber-crunk salacious\" but he added that it fails to be a \"club banger\".<ref name=\"Cibula\">{{cite magazine |last=Cibula |first=Matt |title=Usher: By the Numbers! |url=http://www.popmatters.com/music/reviews/u/usher-confessions.shtml |magazine=[[PopMatters]] |date=April 6, 2004 |accessdate=March 2, 2008}}</ref> Steve Jones of ''[[USA Today]]'' referred to \"Yeah!\" as a \"club-rattling\" song from a combination of \"Atlanta's vibrant music scene\", Lil Jon's \"insistent beats\" and Ludacris' \"racy rhymes\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Steve |title='Confessions' time: Usher continues his ascendancy |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/reviews/2004-03-22-usher-confessions_x.htm |work=[[USA Today]] |publisher=Gannett Co. Inc |date=March 22, 2004 |accessdate=March 3, 2008}}</ref> Robert Hilburn of ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' described \"Yeah!\" as a \"raucous tale of dance-floor seduction\" which [[Pop music|pop]] musician [[Michael Jackson]] would have produced in 2004, if he \"still had the old ''[[Thriller (Michael Jackson album)|Thriller]]'' magic\".<ref name=\"Hilburn\">Hilburn, Robert. [http://articles.latimes.com/2004/mar/21/entertainment/ca-rack21 Review: ''Confessions'']. ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. [[Tribune Company]]. Retrieved on September 13, 2009.</ref>\n\nUsher himself also garnered praise for the song; Aswad called it the \"grittiest song\" Usher had sung and one that \"reveals his newfound maturity\".<ref name=\"Aswad\"/> Caramanica said that it is \"probably the scariest record \u2013 in a good way \u2013 he's ever made\" and Usher \"smartly shares the spotlight.\"<ref name=\"Caramanica\"/> Cibula stated that Usher's \"smoove-ass\" singing and Ludacris' presence contributes to the success of the single.<ref name=\"Cibula\"/> \"Yeah!\" was nominated at the [[Grammy Awards of 2005|2005 Grammy Awards]] for [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], and won the [[Grammy Award for Best Rap/Sung Collaboration|Best Rap/Sung Collaboration]] award.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jeckell |first=Barry |title=Kanye West Leads Grammy Nominees |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/65368/kanye-west-leads-grammy-nominees |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=December 7, 2004 |accessdate=March 2, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title= 47th grammy awards winners announced |url=http://www.ascap.com/eventsawards/awards/grammys/2005/index.html |publisher=ASCAP |accessdate=March 2, 2008}}</ref> At the 2005 [[Soul Train Music Award]]s, \"Yeah!\" was nominated for best R&B/Soul or Rap Dance Cut.<ref name=\"STA\">{{Cite news |author=MTV News Staff |title=For The Record: Quick News On Usher, TLC, Ciara, Beck, Alice In Chains, C-Murder, Beyonc\u00e9, Cher & More |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1496441/20050201/usher.jhtml |publisher=MTV News. Viacom Media Networks |date=February 1, 2005 |accessdate=March 3, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n\"Yeah!\" debuted on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number fifty-three on January 13, 2004 prior to its official release two weeks later.<ref>{{cite web |title=Billboard Hot 100 |url=http://acharts.us/billboard_hot_100/2004/02 |publisher=\u03b1Charts |date=January 13, 2004 |accessdate=March 2, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080223110945/http://acharts.us/billboard_hot_100/2004/02 |archivedate = February 23, 2008}}</ref> On March 2, the song peaked atop the chart and stayed at that position for twelve consecutive weeks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Billboard Hot 100 |url=http://acharts.us/billboard_hot_100/2004/09 |publisher=\u03b1Charts |date=March 2, 2004 |accessdate=March 2, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080120155645/http://acharts.us/billboard_hot_100/2004/09 |archivedate = January 20, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"aCharts\">{{cite web |title=Usher featuring Ludacris and Lil Jon \u2013 Yeah |url=http://acharts.us/song/368 |publisher=\u03b1Charts |accessdate=March 2, 2008}}</ref> \"Yeah!\" became Usher's fourth number-one single, Lil Jon's first and Ludacris' second. The single remained on the Hot 100 for forty-five weeks.<ref name=\"aCharts\"/> \"Yeah!\" became the most played song in the United States in 2004, with Nielsen Broadcast Data Systems reporting the song getting a total of 496,805 plays.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Vineyard |first=Jennifer |title=Usher's 'Yeah!' Was Most Played Song Of 2004 |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1495342/20050105/usher.jhtml |publisher=MTV News. Viacom Media Networks|date=January 5, 2005 |accessdate=March 2, 2008}}</ref> The commercial success of \"Yeah!\" and follow-up single \"[[Burn (Usher song)|Burn]]\" helped sustain ''[[Confessions (Usher album)|Confessions]]'' atop the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart.<ref>{{Cite news |last=D'Angelo |first=Joe |title='Burn' Keeps Usher Hot \u2014 And On Top |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1487119/20040519/usher.jhtml |publisher=MTV News. Viacom Media Networks|date=May 19, 2004 |accessdate=March 3, 2008}}</ref> The single was certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) on June 11, 2006 for shipping one million copies since its release. \"Yeah!\" became the best-performing single of 2004 in the United States.<ref name=\"Hot 100 Year End\">{{cite web|title=2005 Year End Charts \u2013 Hot 100 Songs|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/yearendcharts/2004/hsititl.jsp|publisher= Billboard.BIZ. Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=August 12, 2012}}</ref> The single ranked at number 11 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 All-Time Top Songs,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/specials/hot100/charts/top100-titles-20.shtml|title=The Billboard Hot 100 All-Time Top Songs|year=2008|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=October 19, 2008}}</ref> and second on the Hot 100 decade-end chart, behind [[Mariah Carey]]'s \"[[We Belong Together (Mariah Carey song)|We Belong Together]]\".<ref name=hot100decade/> By September 2013, the song had sold 4 million copies in the US.<ref name=\"yahoosep2013\">{{citation |url= http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/week-ending-sept-15-2013-songs-miley-twerks-195836243.html|title= Week Ending Sept. 15, 2013. Songs: Miley Twerks To The Top |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021234002/http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/week-ending-sept-15-2013-songs-miley-twerks-195836243.html |website=[[Yahoo! Music]] |archive-date=October 21, 2013|access-date=October 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nInternationally, \"Yeah!\" received a similar response, topping several charts. In [[ARIA Charts|Australia]], the song topped the chart on the week of April 4, 2004 for one week. It remained on it for only seven weeks before dropping out, and was certified 5x platinum by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) for selling 350,000 units.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/SinglesAccreds2018.htm|title=SinglesAccreds2018|website=www.aria.com.au|language=en|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref> In [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|New Zealand]], \"Yeah!\" had a better chart performance, peaking at number one for four non-consecutive weeks. It remained on the chart for twenty-seven weeks before dropping and was certified two times platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]] (RIANZ).<ref name=\"newzealandchart\"/> In [[Sverigetopplistan|Switzerland]] and [[\u00d63 Austria Top 75|Austria]], \"Yeah!\" peaked at number one and remained on the charts for thirty-eight and thirty-six weeks, respectively, and was certified gold in both countries.<ref name=\"switzerlandchart\"/><ref name=\"austriachart\"/> The song topped the charts in [[Tracklisten|Denmark]] for three weeks, remaining on the chart for seventeen weeks.<ref name=\"denmarkchart\"/> In [[Single Top 100|Netherlands]], \"Yeah!\" remained number one for four weeks,<ref name=\"dutchchart\"/> and in [[VG-lista|Norway]] for seven weeks.<ref name=\"norwaychart\"/> The song remained number one in [[Irish Singles Chart|Ireland]] for two weeks,<ref name=\"irelandchart\"/> and number one for one week in [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|France]]<ref name=\"francechart\"/> and the [[UK Singles Chart|United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"ukchart\"/> In the latter country, by March 4, 2010, \"Yeah!\" had sold 434,739 copies.<ref>{{cite journal|title=London rules the charts |url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/london-rules-the-charts/042501|work=[[Music Week]]|publisher=Intent Media|date=March 4, 2010|accessdate=April 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nCompared to other countries, \"Yeah!\" under performed in [[The Official Finnish Charts|Finland]], where it stayed on the charts for four weeks and peaked at number seventeen,<ref name=\"finlandchart\"/> and [[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|Spain]] where it peaked at number thirteen.<ref name=\"promusicae\"/> The song did not top the charts in [[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|Italy]] and [[Sverigetopplistan|Sweden]] where it peaked at number three and four,<ref name=\"italychart\"/><ref name=\"swedenchart\"/> respectively, and [[Ultratop 50|Belgium]] (Flanders) and [[Association of Hungarian Record Companies|Hungary]] where it charted at number two.<ref name=\"flanderschart\"/><ref name=\"hungarychart\"/> Overall, the single remained on several charts worldwide for one year, from early 2004 to 2005.<ref name=\"aCharts\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Usher: Yeah |url=http://top40-charts.com/songs/full.php?sid=9066&sort=chartid |publisher=Top40-charts.com |accessdate=March 2, 2008}}</ref> On the 2004 year-end charts, \"Yeah!\" became the twenty-eighth best-selling single in Australia,<ref>{{cite web |title=ARIA Charts \u2013 End Of Year Charts \u2013 Top 100 Singles 2004 |url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-100-singles-2004.htm |publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA)|accessdate=March 2, 2008}}</ref> and twenty-sixth in France.<ref name=\"france yearend\"/> It peaked in the top-ten on the year-end charts in Austria,<ref name=\"austria yearend\"/> Belgium (Flanders),<ref name=\"flanders yearend\"/> Belgium (Wallonia),<ref name=\"wallonia yearend\"/> Netherlands,<ref name=\"dutch yearend\">{{cite web |url=http://www.top40.nl/pdf/Top%20100/top%20100%20-%202004.pdf |title=Single top 100 over 2004 |publisher=Top40 |language=Dutch |format=PDF |accessdate=May 5, 2010}}</ref> Ireland,<ref name=\"ireland yearend\"/> Switzerland<ref name=\"switzerland yearend\"/> and the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"uk yearend\"/>\n\n===Accolades===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Accolade\n! Rank\n|-\n| ''[[Time Magazine]]''\n| Best Songs of 2004<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1999700_1999125_1999111,00.html |title= The Best Songs of 2004 |magazine=Time Magazine |accessdate=17 December 2004}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\u201d| 1\n|-\n| ''[[MTV]]''\n| Most Played Song of 2004<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1495342/ushers-yeah-was-most-played-song-of-2004/ |title=Most Played Song of 200 |magazine=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |accessdate=5 January 2005}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\u201d| 1\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| Top 50 Singles of 2004<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/5933-top-50-singles-of-2004/?page=4 |title=Top 50 Singles of 2004 |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]  |accessdate=30 December 2004}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\u201d| 19\n|-\n| The 200 Best Songs of the 2000s <ref>https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/7693-the-top-500-tracks-of-the-2000s-20-1/?page=2</ref>\n| 175\n|-\n| ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]''\n| The 100 Best Songs of The Complex Decade<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2012/04/the-100-best-songs-of-the-complex-decade/ |title=The 100 Best Songs of The Complex Decade |date=18 April 2012 |magazine=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\u201d| 45\n|-\n| ''Pop Sugar''\n| 30 of the Hottest Songs From the Early '00s <ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.complex.com/music/2012/04/the-100-best-songs-of-the-complex-decade/ |title=30 of the Hottest Songs From the Early '00s |magazine=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |accessdate=18 February 2018}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\u201d| 5\n|-\n| ''[[VH1]]''\n| 100 Greatest Songs of The'00s <ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.stereogum.com/826992/vh1-100-greatest-songs-of-the-00s/franchises/list/ |title=VH1 100 Greatest Songs of the'00s |magazine=VH1 |accessdate=29 September 2011}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\u201d| 27\n|-\n| ''Soul in Stereo''\n| 100 Best R&B Songs Of The 2000s <ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.soulinstereo.com/2019/01/the-100-best-rb-songs-of-the-2000s-presented-by-the-soul-in-stereo-cypher.html |title=100 Best R&B Songs Of The 2000s |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\u201d| 32\n|-\n| ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''\n| The Top 20 Billboard Hot 100 Hits of the 2000s <ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/news/top-20-billboard-hot-100-hits-2000s-040054764.html |title=The Top 20 Billboard Hot 100 Hits of the 2000s |accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\u201d| 2\n|-\n|}\n\n==Music video==\n===Background===\n[[Director X|Mr. X]], formerly Little X, had previously directed videos for Usher's singles \"[[U Don't Have to Call]]\" and \"[[U Got It Bad]]\". Mr. X said that the song reminded him of laser beams.<ref name=\"Gil\">{{Cite news |last=Kaufman |first=Gil |title=Usher's 'Yeah!' A Nod To That Other Laser-Filled Video: VMA Lens Recap |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1490522/20040824/usher.jhtml |publisher=MTV News. Viacom Media Networks|date=August 24, 2004 |accessdate=March 5, 2008}}</ref> Usher and Mr. X combined ideas to create a dance video for \"Yeah!\". The development was handled by how Usher wanted to be portrayed in the video, particularly showcasing his dance moves. The music video was filmed in a vacant art gallery in Los Angeles over two days. When the shooting started, Mr. X recalled [[Michael Jackson]]'s \"low-tech\" and \"laser-flashing\" 1979 \"[[Rock with You]]\" video, and used it as a reference.<ref name=\"Gil\"/> Forty extra people were commissioned to dance with Usher, and two ladies to tempt him in different scenes. They went through photo browsing and phone calling, opting for [[Destiny Lightsy]], a friend of Mr. X, who seduces Usher in the club in a [[Marilyn Monroe]] wardrobe to complement the lyrics.<ref name=\"Gil\"/> Canadian model [[Melyssa Ford]], who was discovered by Mr. X, is portrayed as Usher's second seductress.<ref name=\"Gil\"/> Lil Jon acted as an assistant director during the sessions. Usher took charge of his ideas on his wardrobe and choreography, with additional routines, specifically the Rockaway and the Thunderclap, which Mr. X learned from Jamaica. The Rockaway influenced Fat Joe and Terror Squad's \"[[Lean Back]]\" video.<ref name=\"Gil\"/>\n\n===Synopsis and reception===\n[[File:LittleXFeb07.jpg|200px|thumbnail|right|Canadian director [[Little X|Mr. X]] directed the video for \"Yeah!\"]]\nThe video begins with Usher entering a club, and in another scene dancing in front of blue lasers; the video alternates between both the club and laser scenes throughout. In the former setting, Usher is sat down when a woman\u2014portrayed by Destiny, video producer Mr. X's friend\u2014approaches him and attempts to seduce him. The woman stands up and walks to the dance-floor, telling Usher to \"come get me\" and \"baby let's go\", in sync with the song. Usher goes and dances with her during the chorus. In the beginning of the second verse, the laser scene with Usher dancing now shows both blue and green lasers. Usher and the woman are still dancing, with the woman further attempting to seduce him.\n\nIn the second chorus, Usher performs choreography in the club, backed up by several male dancers. Female dancers then come in, performing choreography along with Usher and the male dancers. After Lil Jon sprays champagne towards the camera in the laser scene, Ludacris performs his verse. He is dancing in both the club and laser scene, with the camera also alternating to female's dancing in sync in the club.\n\nIn the final chorus, Usher again performs choreography in the club, with another scene in the latter setting this time showing a different seductress, portrayed by model Melyssa Ford, walking away telling him to follow her. While following her, he is in a hallway, with the women then pulling Usher in a room, where they begin to romance. While Ludacris says his final verse, rapper [[Chingy]] and [[Sean Combs|P. Diddy]]'s former assistant, [[Fonzworth Bentley]], both make appearances with Bentley holding a violin. Lil Jon says his final verse, not present in the track version of \"Yeah!\", where he repeats numerous dance moves including the Rockaway and Thunderclap, with Usher performing them. The video ends with Lil Jon repeating \"rock away\" and then \"cut\".<ref name=\"ReidShook\"/>\n\nAt the 2004 [[MTV Video Music Awards]], Usher won his first 2 awards with [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Dance Video|Best Dance Video]] and [[Best Male Video]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/66688/2004-mtv-video-music-awards-winners |title=2004 MTV Video Music Awards Winners |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=August 13, 2016}}</ref> At the 2005 [[Soul Train Music Award]]s, the video was nominated for the [[Michael Jackson]] Award for Best R&B/Soul or Rap Music Video.<ref name=\"STA\"/>\n\n==Popular culture==\nThe song has been featured in the films ''[[Hitch (film)|Hitch]], [[The Hangover]],'' and ''[[The Interview]]'' as well as the television shows ''[[House (TV series)|House]]'' and ''[[Getaway (TV series)|Getaway]].'' It has also been in ads for [[Metro by T-Mobile]].\n\nWhen the [[Washington Nationals]] played in [[Montreal|Montreal, Quebec, Canada]] and were known as the [[Montreal Expos]], the song would play over the [[Olympic Stadium (Montreal)|Olympic Stadium]] public address system whenever the opposing team\u2019s at bat list for the next inning would be announced.\n\n==Track listings==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Digital download<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Yeah/dp/B001HXTG3Q/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1344776525&sr=8-1|title=Yeah!: Usher featuring Lil' Jon & Ludacris|publisher=Amazon.uk|accessdate=August 12, 2012}}</ref>\n# \"Yeah!\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:10\n# \"Yeah!\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:10\n\n;Yeah! &ndash; EP<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/yeah!-ep/id252111460|title=Yeah! - EP|publisher=iTunes Store. Apple Inc |accessdate=August 12, 2012}}</ref>\n# \"Yeah!\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:10\n# \"Red Light\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:48\n# \"Sweet Lies\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:09\n# \"Yeah!\" Reggaeton Remix {{small|(Instrumental)}}&nbsp;\u2013 4:09\n\n{{col-2}}\n\n;UK CD 1<ref name=\"UK1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/product/B0001KIH7M/ref=s9_simh_gw_p15_d0_i1?pf_rd_m=A3P5ROKL5A1OLE&pf_rd_s=center-2&pf_rd_r=10QQDTF70KGC506EYCSA&pf_rd_t=101&pf_rd_p=317828027&pf_rd_i=468294|title=Yeah (CD 1): Usher|publisher=[[Amazon.com|Amazon]].uk|accessdate=August 12, 2012}}</ref>\n# \"Yeah!\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:10\n# \"Red Light\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:48\n\n;UK CD 2<ref name=\"UK2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Yeah-Usher-Ludacris-Lil-Jon/dp/B0001KIH72/ref=pd_sim_sbs_m_h__1|title=Yeah (CD 2): Usher|publisher=Amazon.uk|accessdate=August 12, 2012}}</ref>\n# \"Yeah!\"&nbsp;\u2013 4:10\n# \"Red Light\