[Category:2015 singles]]\n[[Category:Epic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Syco Music singles]]\n[[Category:Songs about sexuality]]\n[[Category:Songs with feminist themes]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Priscilla Renea]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Stargate (production team)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Mikkel Storleer Eriksen]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tor Erik Hermansen]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ori Kaplan]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Israel]]\n[[Category:Compositions in C minor]]\n", "text_old": "{{For2|the TV series|[[Worth It (TV series)]]|other uses|[[Worth It (disambiguation)]]}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Worth It\n| cover      = Worth it single cover.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Fifth Harmony]] featuring [[Kid Ink]]\n| album      = [[Reflection (Fifth Harmony album)|Reflection]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2015|3|2}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single|CD]]|[[Music download|digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| recorded   = 2014\n| studio     = {{Collapsible list|title=Various|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:12px;background:transparent;text-align:left|\n{{Plainlist|\n*Windmark Recording <br>{{small|([[Santa Monica, California]])}}\n*[[Westlake Recording Studios|Westlake]] and R8D Studios<br>{{small|([[West Hollywood, California]])}}\n*The Hide Out Studios <br>{{small|([[London]], [[United Kingdom]])}}\n}}}}\n| genre      = {{Flat list |\n* [[Dance-pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=44}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Epic Records|Epic]]|[[Syco Music|Syco]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Priscilla Renea]]|[[Stargate (music producers)|Mikkel S. Eriksen]]|[[Stargate (music producers)|Tor Erik Hermansen]]|[[Ori Kaplan]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Stargate|Ori Kaplan}}\n| chronology = [[Fifth Harmony]]\n| prev_title = [[Sledgehammer (Fifth Harmony song)|Sledgehammer]]\n| prev_year  = 2014\n| next_title = [[I'm in Love with a Monster]]\n| next_year  = 2015\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Kid Ink]]\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[Ride Out]]\n | prev_year  = 2015\n | title      = Worth It\n | year       = 2015\n | next_title = [[Be Real (Kid Ink song)|Be Real]]\n | next_year  = 2015\n}}{{External music video|{{YouTube|YBHQbu5rbdQ|\"Worth It\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Worth It'''\" is a song performed by American [[girl group]] [[Fifth Harmony]], featuring American rapper [[Kid Ink]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lindner|first=Emilee|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2053459/fifth-harmony-worth-it-dirty-kid-ink/|title=Is Fifth Harmony\u2019s New Song \u2018Worth It\u2019 Even Bossier Than \u2018Bo$$\u2019?|publisher=MTV|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=January 20, 2015}}</ref> The song impacted American [[rhythmic crossover]] radio on March 2, 2015 as the third and final single from the group's debut studio album, ''[[Reflection (Fifth Harmony album)|Reflection]]'' (2015). Written by [[Priscilla Renea]] and its producers [[Stargate (music producers)|Stargate]], \"Worth It\" is a [[dance-pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song that incorporates a strong use of [[Balkan music]] and [[Middle Eastern music]] in its production, the trademark of its producer and songwriter, [[Ori Kaplan]]. The lyrics discuss themes of [[feminism]], self-worth and confidence, and include [[double entendre]]s.\n\nThe song became a [[sleeper hit]] on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] where it peaked at number 12, marking the group's highest charting single at the time<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://m.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6642164/omi-cheerleader-third-week-hot-100|title=OMI's 'Cheerleader' No. 1 for Third Week on Hot 100 &#124; Billboard|magazine=Billboard|date=July 27, 2015 |accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref> and the first top 20 single by a girl group in the US since \"[[Jai Ho! (You Are My Destiny)]]\" by [[The Pussycat Dolls]] in 2009. It reached number three on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. Directed by Cameron Duddy, the music video has themes of female empowerment with Fifth Harmony dominating men as business executives. It has received over a billion views on [[YouTube]]. The group promoted \"Worth It\" with several televised performances, including the [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 21)|season twenty-one]] finale of ''[[Dancing with the Stars]]'', ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' and at the [[2015 MTV Europe Music Awards]].\n\n==Background and development==\n[[File:Ori Kaplan.jpg|thumb|215px|alt=|[[Ori Kaplan]], who produced \"[[Talk Dirty (Jason Derulo song)|Talk Dirty]]\" by [[Jason Derulo]], also co-produced and co-wrote \"Worth It\".]]\n\"Worth It\" was produced and co-written by Norwegian production company, [[Stargate (production team)|Stargate]], consisting of duo Mikkel S. Eriksen and Tor Erik Hermansen and [[Ori Kaplan]], with additional writing from [[Priscilla Renea]]. The song was released on January 15, 2015 on streaming and downloading services but officially impacted American [[rhythmic crossover]] radio as a single on March 2, 2015.<ref name=\"Top 40 Rhythmic Future Releases\">{{cite web|title=Top 40 Rhythmic Future Releases|url=http://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|publisher=All Access Media Group|accessdate=January 30, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130230409/http://www.allaccess.com/top40-rhythmic/future-releases|archivedate=30 January 2015}}</ref> A Spanish version titled \"{{lang|es|Dame Esta Noche|italic=}}\" (Spanish for \"Give Me This Night\") was released to [[iTunes]] on July 10, 2015, following the success of the single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/worth-it-dame-esta-noche-feat./id1018370557?app=itunes|title=Worth It (Dame Esta Noche) [feat. Kid Ink&#93; - Single by Fifth Harmony on iTunes|publisher=iTunes|date=July 10, 2015|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref> The track features Kid Ink's English rap verse, while the group sings in Spanish.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6633540/fifth-harmony-dame-esta-noche-worth-it-spanish-version|title=Fifth Harmony Drop 'Dame Esta Noche,' Spanish Version of 'Worth It': Listen|magazine=Billboard|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOriginally intended for recording by rapper [[Kid Ink]], who ended up collaborating on the song, the lyrics and melody were changed to fit a female perspective. Kid Ink noted during an interview with ''[[Forbes]]'' that while he was \"writing on their album\", he was able to collaborate with \"producers Stargate and [[Cashmere Cat]]\" and this led to the development of the song.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/shawnsetaro/2015/03/31/kid-inks-furious-rise-to-the-top/|title=Kid Ink's Furious Rise To The Top|magazine=Forbes|date=March 31, 2015|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref> One of Kid Ink's verses from \"Wit It\" (the original version of the song) appears on this song.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dpsEa-3JMQg|title=Kid Ink - Wit It (Feat. The Ranger$)|publisher=YouTube|date=March 5, 2015|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref> Speaking to ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'', Dinah Jane explained that the song was unplanned for the album, saying \"there were no females on the song\". After the song was presented to them by production team Stargate, they changed part of the lyrics and bits \"of the concept\" to \"fit [their] perspective\". Lauren Jauregui also shared similar sentiments, saying that she \"didn't think\" the track would \"make the album\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2015/06/fifth-harmony-interview-worth-it-reflections-tour|title= Interview: Fifth Harmony Talk Their Platinum Hit \"Worth It\" and Their Love for Drake, Fetty Wap, and Kendrick Lamar|magazine= Complex|date= June 22, 2015|access-date= March 10, 2017}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', music director David Armbrecht explained that the song is a \"message of [[self-empowerment]], which is made clear in its triumphant 'Give it to me, I'm worth it!' chorus\". The song speaks to women of \"all demographics\", he said, explaining that this can be applied to anyone in a \"relationship\" or \"getting out of one\" and it is likely that one can get \"tired of the games\" and deserve better, using the song to do just that.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6641068/fifth-harmony-selena-gomez-demi-lovato-hot-100|title=Hot 100 Chart Moves: Fifth Harmony Ups Its 'Worth,' Selena Gomez & Demi Lovato Gain|magazine=Billboard|date= July 22, 2015|access-date= March 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n{{Listen\n| filename= Fifth Harmony and Kid Ink - Worth It.ogg\n| title= \"Worth It\" \n| description= \"Worth It\" takes its music from a variety of instrumentation, as a [[Trap music (hip hop)|trap]]-inspired Roland TR-808, heavy [[bass (sound)|bassline]], [[handclap]]s and a [[saxophone]] as its foundation. Several music critics noted that \"Worth It\" production is comparable to \"[[Talk Dirty (Jason Derulo song)|Talk Dirty]]\" by [[Jason Derulo]] for similar use of [[horn (instrument)|horn]]s.<ref name=\"fuse\"/><ref name=\"pitchfork\"/>\n}}\nMusically, \"Worth It\" incorporates [[dance-pop]] and [[contemporary R&B]] with influences of [[hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[Balkan music]].<ref name=\"salon.com\">{{cite news|author=Sonia Saraiya |url=http://www.salon.com/2015/08/11/im_worth_it_how_a_self_help_refrain_became_the_pop_anthem_of_the_summer/|title=\"I\u2019m worth it\": How a self-help refrain became the pop anthem of the summer|work=Salon|date=August 11, 2015|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"m.mic.com\">{{cite web|author=Mic|url=http://m.mic.com/articles/121460/14-recent-pop-songs-that-are-basically-the-same-song|title=14 Recent Pop Songs That Are Basically the Same Song - Mic|publisher=.Mic|date=June 30, 2015|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"time\">{{cite magazine|author=Jamieson Cox|url=http://time.com/3692465/fifth-harmony-reflection-album-review/|title=Fifth Harmony 'Reflection' Album Review|magazine=Time|date=February 3, 2015|accessdate=April 6, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"mtv1\">{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2053459/fifth-harmony-worth-it-kid-ink/|title=Is Fifth Harmony's New Song 'Worth It' Even Bossier Than 'Bo$$'?|publisher=MTV|date=January 20, 2015|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://poptius.com/2015/01/22/fifth-harmony-get-horny-with-worth-it-review/ |title=Fifth Harmony Get Horny With \"Worth It\" (Review)|publisher=Poptius|date=January 22, 2015|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://axs.com/the-top-10-best-fifth-harmony-songs-79234|title=The Top 10 Best Fifth Harmony Songs|publisher=AXS|date=May 21, 2016|accessdate=March 29, 2017}}</ref> The song contains elements from a variety of music genres. It can be noted mainly in its instrumentation, which incorporates a [[Middle Eastern]]-inflected [[saxophone]],<ref name=\"salon.com\"/><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/billboard-lists/6859179/zumba-pop-playlist|title= Pop Workout Playlist: 15 Body-Movin' Tunes to Rock Your Fitness Routine|magazine= Billboard|date= February 2, 2016|access-date= March 29, 2017}}</ref> [[trance music|trance]] [[synthesizer (music)|synths]] and a [[Trap music (hip hop)|trap]]-inspired [[Roland TR-808]] [[drum]] machine.<ref name =pitchfork>{{cite web|last=Garvey|first=Meaghan|date=February 11, 2015|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/20253-reflection/|title=Fifth Harmony:Reflection|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]|accessdate=February 11, 2015}}</ref> Songwriting and production is largely based on previous Kaplan and Stargate's productions, most notably [[Jason Derulo]]'s \"[[Talk Dirty (Jason Derulo song)|Talk Dirty]]\", which shows similar song scheme and use of [[horn (instrument)|horn]]s during the [[Motif (music)|hook]].<ref name=\"fuse\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/videos/2015/03/fifth-harmony-worth-it-video-kid-ink|title=Fifth Harmony Step Up as New-Age Feminist Icons in \"Worth It\" Video|accessdate= June 13, 2015|date=March 30, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"pitchfork\"/><ref name=\"m.mic.com\"/> The song is written from the perspective of a woman telling a man that she is \"Worth It\", implying sexual connotation.<ref name=\"plugged\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pluggedin.com/music-reviews/track/fifth-harmony-worth-it/|title= Fifth Harmony - Wroth It|work= Plugged In|date= March 3, 2015|access-date= March 6, 2017}}</ref> However, it can be considered as a [[feminism|feminist]] anthem, according to Jeff Benjamin from [[Fuse (magazine)|Fuse]], it can inspire \"young girls to truly believe they're 'Worth It' and can own [[Wall Street]] or any other place on which they set their sights\". This latter view of the song is highlighted in its music video.<ref name=\"fuse\"/>\n\nThe song opens with a [[saxophone]] sample that introduces the repetitive hook, where the group sings repeatedly the phrase \"Give it to me, I'm worth it\", backed by heavy [[bass (sound)|bassline]] and \"trappy beats\"<ref name=\"fuse\"/><ref name=\"salon.com\"/><ref name=\"plugged\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theedgesusu.co.uk/records/singles/2015/07/08/review-fifth-harmony-ft-kid-ink-worth-it/|title=Review: Fifth Harmony ft. Kid Ink \u2013 \u2018Worth It'|publisher=The Edge|date=July 18, 2015|accessdate= March 29, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Digitalspy\"/> Followed by [[Kid Ink]]'s rapped verse, Emilee Linder of [[MTV]] noted he insists that they \"bring it back like they left something\".<ref name=\"mtv1\"/> The member Dinah Jane then is introduced, backgrounded with [[Clapping|handclaps]], Normani Kordei performs the pre-chorus (which is then performed by Ally Brooke after the second verse),<ref name=\"m.mic.com\"/> while the second verse is sung by [[Camila Cabello]], who delivers the song's most suggestive lines, \"Come harder just because/I don't like it, like it too soft/I like it a little rough/Not too much, but maybe just enough\".<ref name=\"mtv1\"/><ref name=\"plugged\"/> [[Lauren Jauregui]] is the only member of the band that doesn\u2019t sing in the song. According to the sheet music published by [[Sony Music Publishing]] at Musicnotes.com, the song is written in the key of [[C minor]] and is set in a  {{music|time|4|4}} [[time signature]] with a moderate [[tempo]] of 100 [[beats per minute]]. Fifth Harmony and Kid Ink's vocal range spans from the low note of G<sub>3</sub> to the high note of Ab<sub>5</sub>. The saxophone's melody spans the tonal range of E<sub>4</sub> to C<sub>6</sub>.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0155674|title= Fifth Harmony \"Worth It\" Sheet Music|publisher= musicnotes.com|work=[[Sony Music Publishing]]|access-date= March 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\"Worth It\" received mixed reviews from music critics, receiving praise for its catchy rhythm and attitude but was criticized for sounding similar to Jason Derulo's \"Talk Dirty\". Rick Florino from [[Artistdirect]] praised \"Worth It\", giving it a five out of five star rating, claiming the song has \"an empowering refrain that's impossible to shake, especially when coupled with a slippery beat\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/album-review-fifth-harmony-reflection-5-out-of-5-stars/11314051|title=Album Review: Fifth Harmony \"Reflection\" \u2013 5-out-of-5 stars|date=February 4, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref> FDRMX also reviewed it positively, mentioning that \"the production is solid and the lyrics are catchy\" and also stating that the single is Fifth Harmony's most mature record yet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fdrmx.com/fifth-harmony-worth-single-review/|title=REVIEW: Fifth Harmony: \u2018Worth It\u2019 Single Review|date=January 20, 2015|accessdate=June 13, 2015}}</ref> Several music publications considered it a strong contender for song of the summer.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Song of the Summer: Taylor Swift, Britney Spears & Iggy Azalea, Maroon 5 and Other Early Contenders|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6568305/2015-song-of-the-summer-taylor-swift-britney-spears-iggy-azalea-maroon-5|website=Billboard|accessdate=3 July 2017|date=15 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lamarre|first1=Carl|title=Interview: Fifth Harmony Talk Their Platinum Hit \"Worth It\" and Their Love for Drake, Fetty Wap, and Kendrick Lamar|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2015/06/fifth-harmony-interview-worth-it-reflections-tour|website=Complex|accessdate=3 July 2017|date=22 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Zeichner|first1=Naomi|title=What Will The Song of Summer Be? 15 Options|url=http://www.thefader.com/2015/04/29/song-of-summer|website=The Fader|accessdate=3 July 2017|date=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nRebecca Mattina, from ''Andpop'' gave the song a mixed review, noting too-close a similarity to \"[[Talk Dirty (Jason Derulo song)|Talk Dirty]]\" but also stating that the track is \"filled with lots of attitude\" and rhythmic bounce.<ref name=\"andpop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.andpop.com/2015/01/27/track-track-review-reflection-fifth-harmony/|title=Track-by-Track Review: Reflection by Fifth Harmony|date=January 27, 2015|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref> Conversely, Music Times gave it a positive review stating 'the intense, creeping music of \"Worth It\" is matched with deep harmonies from 5H and personally positive lyrics\". They made a comparison to the first lead single of ''Reflection'' (2015), \"[[Boss (Fifth Harmony song)|Boss]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/25224/20150120/fifth-harmony-worth-it-review-listen-stream-reflection.htm|title=REVIEW: Fifth Harmony Prove They're \"Worth It\"|date=January 20, 2015|accessdate=June 13, 2015}}</ref> In a review for their debut album, ''Reflection'' (2015), Meaghan Garvey of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' commented that the song is an \"exhaustive exquisite corpse of practically every radio hit of the last year and a half\" and criticizes the \"wholly unremarkable rap verse\" performed by Kid Ink.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Garvey|first1=Meaghan|title=Fifth Harmony: Reflection Album Review|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/20253-reflection/|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=June 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a negative review, Jason Lipshutz from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', stated that the song sounded \"oddly incomplete.\" Lipshutz also highlighted the song's \"repetitive phrasing.\"<ref name=Billboard>{{cite web|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|date=February 2, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/6458265/fifth-harmony-reflection-track-by-track-review|title=Fifth Harmony Shows Who's Bo$$ on 'Reflection': Track-by-Track Review|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=February 3, 2015}}</ref> In a mixed-positive review, Amy Davidson, from ''[[Digital Spy]]'', noted that \"trumpets and saxophones have experienced a resurgence [and Fifth Harmony] have laid it on thick for some serious sax-sampling. 'Give it to me I'm worth it,' they determine, dripping with sass.\" Davidson also stated, \"It mightn't be the most groundbreaking of tracks, but it's got enough attitude to forgive that.\"<ref name=\"Digitalspy\">{{cite web|last=Davidson|first=Amy|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/feature/a656469/this-weeks-new-singles-reviewed-years--years-fifth-harmony-conor-maynard.html#~piYY7pv98mUCRv|title=This week's new singles reviewed: Years & Years, Fifth Harmony, Conor Maynard - Music Feature|website=Digital Spy|date=July 5, 2015|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref> For their year-end list of best songs, ''[[Associated Press]]'' listed it at number three<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berkshireeagle.com/entertainment/ci_29274230/associated-press-rates-best-songs-2015|title=The Associated Press rates the best songs of 2015|work= Berkshire Eagle}}</ref> and ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' ranked it at 68.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2015/11/the-101-best-songs-of-2015/2/|title=The 101 Best Songs of 2015|work=Spin}}</ref> [[Artistdirect]] ranked the song at number one in their mid-year report.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/15-best-songs-of-2015-so-far/11752359|title=15 Best Songs of 2015 So Far|work=Artistdirect}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n===North America===\nOn the chart dated February 7, 2015, \"Worth It\" debuted on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number 82.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-02-07|title=Music: Top 100 Songs &#124; Billboard Hot 100 Chart|magazine=Billboard|date=February 7, 2015|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref> It would exit the chart the following week and re-enter on the third week at number 93.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hot 100: The Week of February 21, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-02-21|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> On the [[Mainstream Top 40]] and [[Rhythmic (chart)|Rhythmic]] charts, the song debuted at 39 and 38, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Chart Highlights: 'Loud' & Proud, Ed Sheeran Tops All Three Pop, Adult Airplay Charts|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6495056/chart-highlights-loud-proud-ed-sheeran-tops-all-three-pop-adult|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2015|date=9 March 2015}}</ref> On the main chart, it would exit once again, this time for four weeks, before charting at number 92.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hot 100: The Week of March 21, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-03-21|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> For the week dated March 28, 2015, the song rose five spots to a new position at number 87.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hot 100: The Week of March 28, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-03-28|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> Following the release of the music video, which premiered at the Kid's Choice Awards, the song rose nine spots to number 78.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hot 100: The Week of April 4, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-04-04|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> The promotion from the video and the show's audience gave the song a 20 spot jump at number 58 for the week dated April 11, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hot 100: The Week of April 11, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-04-11|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> For the week dated April 18, 2015, the song rose 17 spots to a peak of 41.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hot 100: The Week of April 18, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-04-18|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> The following week, the song rose two spots at a new peak of 39, earning the group their second top 40 hit and their highest charting single at the time of the publication. It recorded 48,000 digital sales, a five percent slip from the previous week and a four percent increase at 3.6 million streams.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Hot 100 Chart Moves: Fifth Harmony's Wait for Highest-Charting Hit 'Worth It'|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6538618/hot-100-fifth-harmony-highest-charting-hit|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017|date=17 April 2015}}</ref> On the Mainstream Top 40 chart, the song would peak at number four, earning them their first top 10 hit as well as their first entry in the Rhythmic chart, where the song peaked at number 19<ref>{{cite web|last=Cantor|first=Brian|url=http://headlineplanet.com/home/2015/03/08/iggy-azalea-jennifer-hudson-fifth-harmony-reach-pops-top-40/|title=Iggy Azalea & Jennifer Hudson, Fifth Harmony, Shaggy Reach Pop's Top 40|publisher=Headline Planet|date=May 26, 2015|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"US Pop Songs Worth It\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/5665538/Fifth+Harmony/chart?f=381|title=Fifth Harmony Album & Song Chart History |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFor the week dated May 2, 2015, the song rose five more spots to a peak of number 34 and two more spots the following week.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hot 100: The Week of May 2, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-05-02|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Hot 100: The Week of May 9, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-05-09|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> The song rose 11 spots again to a new peak of 21, for the week dated May 16, 2015 and would be stationary for another week.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hot 100: The Week of May 16, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-05-16|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Hot 100: The Week of May 23, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-05-23|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> The next week, the song rose two more spots at a new peak of 19, earning the group their first top 20 single, gaining radio airplay by 18 percent at a 31 million audience.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Hot 100 Chart Moves: Fifth Harmony Scores First Top 20 Hit|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6575747/fifth-harmony-first-top-20-hit-hot-100-chart-moves|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017|date=22 May 2015}}</ref> This occurred a week after a minor controversy, where the group was scheduled to perform the track on the [[Billboard Music Awards]] but instead presented an award, citing time issues with the rehearsal and production of the song. Instead, they opted for a performance of the song at the season twenty finale of ''Dancing with the Stars''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Love|first1=Ryan|title=Fifth Harmony explain why they pulled their Billboard Music Awards performance|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a648282/fifth-harmony-explain-why-they-pulled-their-billboard-music-awards-performance/|website=Digital Spy|accessdate=2 July 2017|date=19 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gracie|first1=Bianca|title=Fifth Harmony Perform \"Worth It\" On \u2018Dancing With The Stars\u2019 Season Finale: Watch|url=http://www.idolator.com/7593716/fifth-harmony-perform-worth-it-on-dwts-season-finale-watch|website=Idolator|accessdate=2 July 2017|date=20 May 2015}}</ref> For the week dated June 6, 2015, the song rose two spots to number 17.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hot 100: The Week of June 6, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-06-06|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> It would fall one spot for the week dated June 13, 2015 and would stay there for one week before rising three spots to number 15.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hot 100: The Week of June 27, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/2015-06-27|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> The song would rise one spot and staying at number 14, recording a rise of 7 percent at a 79 million audience for radio airplay and charting at number 10 on the Radio Songs chart for the week dated July 22, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Trust|first1=Gary|title=Hot 100 Chart Moves: Fifth Harmony Ups Its 'Worth,' Selena Gomez & Demi Lovato Gain|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6641068/fifth-harmony-selena-gomez-demi-lovato-hot-100|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017|date=22 July 2015}}</ref> The song would reach its peak of number 12 on the chart dated August 8, 2015, becoming the week's streaming gainer.<ref name=\"US Hot 100 Worth It\">{{cite web|url= http://www.billboard.com/artist/5665538/Fifth+Harmony/chart?f=379|title= Fifth Harmony Album & Song Chart History|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref> Since its release, the song has sold over 1,700,000 copies, according to a publication from ''Billboard'', on May 12, 2017.<ref name=\"Worth It sales\">{{cite web|last1=Gensler|first1=Andy|title=L.A. Reid's Epic Reign, By the Numbers|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7793043/la-reid-epic-reign-by-the-numbers|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017|date=12 May 2017}}</ref> It achieved a triple platinum certification by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]], for combined sales and track-equivalent streams units of three million;<ref name=\"US Worth It certification\"/> as of 2016 it was one of only twenty-two songs released in 2015 to be certified multi-platinum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://li.st/l/3gIMVYj0vPSd8Eicw3GxmV|title=Top 15 in 2015 - RIAA Gold & Platinum Awards Edition|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216151117/https://li.st/l/3gIMVYj0vPSd8Eicw3GxmV|archive-date=February 16, 2016|date=February 16, 2016|work=The List App/RIAA}}</ref>\n\nThe song debuted at number 92 in Canada on the week marked April 11, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Billboard Canadian Hot 100: The Week of April 11, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/canadian-hot-100/2015-04-11|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> For the following week, the song rose 25 spots at a position at number 67 and then another the week after that. It would rise 12 spots once again for the week dated May 2, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Billboard Canadian Hot 100: The Week of May 2, 2017|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/canadian-hot-100/2015-05-02|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> The song would rise one spot for two consecutive weeks, before staying stationary for one week. It continued to rise in positions, two spots then six spots to a peak at number 44 for the week of June 6, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Billboard Canadian Hot 100: The Week of June 6, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/canadian-hot-100/2015-06-06|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref>\nIt would rise another ten spots to peak at number 34, earning the group their first top 40 entry in this market.<ref>{{cite web|title=Billboard Canadian Hot 100: The Week of June 13, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/canadian-hot-100/2015-06-13|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> The following week, the song continued its rise, jumping 13 spots to number 21. It would rise once again, peaking at number 16, and earning the group their first top 20 entry as well for the week dated June 27, 2015. It rose one spot for two consecutive weeks before falling two spots at number 16. After a series of drops and rises, the song would peak at number 12, on the week of September 5, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Billboard Canadian Hot 100: The Week of September 5, 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/canadian-hot-100/2015-09-05|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> It was certified double platinum for selling over 160,000 digital copies. In Mexico, the song topped both its English and domestic charts. It was subsequently promoted through a Spanish release, where the group sang their verses in Spanish. It was certified platinum for selling 60,000 copies.\n\n===Elsewhere===\nThe song was released in the United Kingdom through digital download on June 21, 2015, over six months since being released in the United States market and more than three months later since receiving airplay there as well. For the week of July 4, 2015, the song debuted on the [[Official Charts Company]] at number 81.<ref>{{cite web|title=Official Singles Chart Top 100 (28 June 2015 - 04 July 2015)|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20150628/7501/|website=Official Charts Company|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> It rose thirty spots to a peak of 51, the following week. For the week dated July 16, 2015, the song rose 48 spots to a peak at number 3, earning the group their first top five entry on the chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Official Singles Chart Top 100 (10 July 2015 - 16 July 2015)|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20150710/7501/|website=Official Charts Company|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> The song would stay in the top 40 for eight additional weeks and would chart for a total of 19 weeks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Official Charts: Fifth Harmony ft. Kid Ink|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/47734/fifth-harmony-ft-kid-ink/|website=Official Charts Company|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> The song peaked in the top 20 of nine additional countries. In Hungary, the song entered the top 10 of the country's three domestic charts, rising six spots to a peak of number 2 on the week of September 20, 2015 on the singles chart. On the dance and radios chart, the song rose three spots for the same week as the singles chart, to a peak of seven and rose one spot to a peak at number four, respectively. In the French charts, the song peaked at number 15 and charted for a total of 29 weeks. Similarly, in Germany, the song peaked at number 16 and would chart for 31 weeks.\n\nIn Australia, the song would peak at number nine, earning the group their first top 10 entry in this market. The song would stay in the top 10 for an additional week and would chart for a total of fifteen weeks. Conversely, in the New Zealand market, the song failed to reach the top 20, charting at 31 and appearing on the chart for fourteen weeks. The song received airplay in Middle Eastern markets, topping the charts in both Israel and Lebanon. The song's blend of Balkan music, which has been a staple in the [[Middle East]], aided in its success in this region. The song debuted at number 98 on the Japanese Hot 100 for the week January 23, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Japan Hot 100: The Week of January 23, 2016|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/japan-hot-100/2016-01-23|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> The following week, it rose 44 spots to a new peak of 54.<ref>{{cite web|title=Japan Hot 100: The Week of January 30, 2016|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/japan-hot-100/2016-01-30|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> It would rise 25 more spots to a new position at number 29 and then three spots to a position at 26, where it would reach its peak.<ref>{{cite web|title=Japan Hot 100: The Week of February 13, 2016|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/japan-hot-100/2016-02-13|website=Billboard|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> Across seas, the song peaked at 53 on the Brazilian ''Billboard'' Hot 100, making its first appearance on this chart.\n\n==Music video==\n===Background and reception===\n{{Quote box\n| quote = \"We also wanted to incorporate feminism and girl power and our fans, so we kind of did this Twitter thing where we... told them to send in tweets saying why they think feminism is sexy and why they think it\u2019s cool and why they think women empowerment is awesome.\"\n| source = \u2014[[Camila Cabello]] talking to MTV about fans' tweets that appear in the music video.<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2118445/fifth-harmony-worth-it-video/|title=Fifth Harmony Go All \u201950 Shades\u2019 Of Feminist In Their \u2018Worth It\u2019 Video|date=July 20, 2015}}</ref>\n| align = right\n| width = 30%\n}}\nThe music video premiered at the [[2015 Kids' Choice Awards]] on March 28, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6516823/fifth-harmony-premieres-worth-it-video-at-nickelodeon-kids-choice-awards|title=Fifth Harmony Premieres 'Worth It' Video at Kids' Choice Awards|date=March 28, 2015|access-date=June 6, 2015}}</ref> It was uploaded the same day to the group's official [[Vevo]] account and directed by Cameron Duddy.<ref name=\"Worth It video\"/><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2015/03/29/video-fifth-harmony-kid-ink-worth-it/|title=Video: Fifth Harmony feat. Kid Ink \u2013 \u2018Worth It\u2019|magazine=Rap-Up|date=March 29, 2015|access-date=June 6, 2015}}</ref> The video follows a similar concept from their lead single, \"[[Boss (Fifth Harmony song)|Boss]]\", focusing on themes of [[Self-esteem|self-worth]], [[confidence]] and [[Women's empowerment|female empowerment]]. The \"Worth It\" music video earned Fifth Harmony their first Vevo certified award in July 2015<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Ben|title=Fifth Harmony become the first girl group to pass a billion views of a single music video on YouTube|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a802916/fifth-harmony-become-the-first-girl-group-to-pass-a-billion-views-of-a-single-music-video-on-youtube/|website=Digital Spy|access-date=June 9, 2017}}</ref> and later reached the one-billion-view mark on July 27, 2016. With over 1.8 billion views, it is now one of the 60 most viewed YouTube videos of all time and the second-most watched YouTube video by a girl group, being overtaken at the number one spot for most watched video with \"Work from Home\", which was released a nearly a year later.<ref name=\"Worth It video\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YBHQbu5rbdQ|title=Fifth Harmony - Worth It ft. Kid Ink|publisher=YouTube|date=March 28, 2015|access-date=November 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nCritics were positively receptive of the video, some calling the visuals \"sexy\" and commending the message of female empowerment that is the group executes. In a positive review, [[MTV]] called it \"surprisingly sexy\" and compared the office look of the video to ''[[Fifty Shades of Grey (film)|Fifty Shades of Grey]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2118445/fifth-harmony-worth-it-video/|title=Fifth Harmony Go All '50 Shades' Of Feminist In Their 'Worth It' Video|publisher=MTV|date=March 28, 2015|access-date=September 13, 2015}}</ref> Christina Lee from [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] praised the video for putting women in position of power. She notes the video's ambiguous message, but knows there is a \"clear difference between women dressing for the male gaze and doing so for their own personal satisfaction.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7586347/fifth-harmony-worth-it-video|title=Fifth Harmony Debuts \"Worth It\" Video: Watch|work=Idolator}}</ref> The video was abruptly deleted from [[YouTube]] on July 18. At the time, a static screen appeared that read, \"This video has been removed as a violation of YouTube's policy on repetitive, misleading or inappropriate metadata.\" It was later re-uploaded with the previous views intact. When reached to comment on the issue, a spokesperson for YouTube later commented saying that videos can be taken down by mistake but a review is taken to take \"appropriate action\", which include restoring videos that were previously removed. However, there could be another reason why it was taken down, which is because of its sexualized portrayal of Cabello and Jane, who were [[underage]]{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=February 2019}} when the video was filmed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Walker|first1=John|title=Here's why Fifth Harmony's 'Worth It' video was removed from YouTube|url=http://fusion.kinja.com/heres-why-fifth-harmonys-worth-it-video-was-removed-fro-1793849391|website=Fusion|access-date=June 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Synopsis===\nThe video begins with shots of the skyline of [[Hong Kong]], where most of the setting takes place. An image of a stock market appears, zooming in on what appears to say, \"@FifthHarmony [[Women in positions of power|women in power]]\". The girls then appear in silhouettes and begin walking confidently as men stand next to a wall, appearing to stand in attention to the ladies. Individual shots of every girl are shown, giggling and smiling at the camera, before switching back to the stock market background. The group perform a choreographed dance move, and a [[Newton's cradle]] is shown being used, in rhythm to the song. The words \"break through the [[glass ceiling]]\" appear in stock market background, a reference to the obstacles that minorities, particularly minority women, have when climbing the corporate ladder.\n[[File:Fifth Harmony - Worth It ft. Kid Ink Music Video.png|thumb|250px|right|alt=|The members of [[Fifth Harmony]] dress in business-esque attire, demonstrating themes of [[feminism]] and [[Self-esteem|self-worth]].]]\nThe verse changes to Kid Ink, who is dressed in almost all-black clothing. He appears to be sitting in an office room with two attractive women approaching him as he sings. The women are dressed in business attire and are shown to have green eyes, known as a symbol for greed and/or jealousy. A man is shown cleaning Dinah's shoe, as she controls him. She then kicks him to show she is not controlled by anyone. The scene shifts to Normani, who is sporting a fashionable business outfit with a white blazer. She then dramatically stands up from her chair, while a man, who appears to be her accountant, looks at her in a frightened motion. Just like the women sitting next to Kid Ink, he also appears to have green eyes. All members perform a dance move, when the setting shifts to Camila getting ready to play golf in her office. Ally is then shown with a man who also appears to be her accountant, similar to Normani. Lauren is seen in the back of a convertible black car with a man in the driver's seat. Each girl either flicks the man next to them or kicks them in frustration.\n\nThe ladies are now in the stock market background, telling their lover that they're \"Worth It\". They also seem to rush their accountants, who are continuously typing on their calculators. The words ''\"[[feminism]] is sexy\"'' appear in the stock market background, before switching to Kid Ink, where the women move in-sync to the rhythm as he raps. The camera zooms into the eyes of a woman, with her eyes appearing bright green. The group perform more choreographed dance moves individually and as a group. Shots of all the members winking their eye, smiling, and showing confidence are shown. The video ends with the group facing away from the camera and looking at the stock market behind them, then turn around and move their hands upward, a similar ending to the group's past videos.\n\n==Live performances==\nFifth Harmony performed \"Worth It\" live for the first time on [[VH1]]'s ''[[Big Morning Buzz Live]]'' on February 17, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stern|first1=Bradley|title=Fifth Harmony Perform \"Worth It\" Live For The First Time: Watch|url=http://www.idolator.com/7581536/fifth-harmony-performance-worth-it-live-watch|publisher=Idolator|accessdate=February 20, 2015}}</ref> They performed the song on ''[[Live! with Kelly and Michael]]'' on April 13,<ref>{{cite web|title=Fifth Harmony Perform \"Worth It\" On \u2018Live With Kelly & Michael': Watch {{!}} Idolator|url=http://www.idolator.com/7588702/fifth-harmony-worth-it-live-kelly-michael-watch|accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> as well as on the [[Radio Disney Music Awards]] which aired on April 26, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2015/04/27/fifth-harmony-performance-radio-disney-music-awards-2015-worth-it-video/|title=Fifth Harmony Rocks \u2018Worth It\u2019 At Radio Disney Music Awards \u2014 Watch|last=Wilson|first=Samantha|date=April 27, 2015|work=Hollywood Life|accessdate=May 25, 2015}}</ref> The song was also performed on the finale of ''[[Dancing with the Stars]]'' on May 19, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latintimes.com/pulse/watch-fifth-harmony-dancing-stars-finale-performance-totally-worth-it-video-317819|title=Watch Fifth Harmony 'Dancing With The Stars' Finale Performance Totally 'Worth It' [VIDEO]|accessdate=June 6, 2015}}</ref> Outside of the United States, the group performed for the first time in the United Kingdom at ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]'' on June 5, 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/goodmorningbritain/entertainment/fifth-harmony-are-worth-it-simon-cowell|title=Fifth Harmony get their inspiration from Spice Girls|publisher=ITV|date=June 5, 2015|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref> as well as Capital FM's [[Summertime Ball]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] the following day<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/fifth-harmony/news/summertime-ball-lineup-2015/|title=#Harmonizers... Your Ladies Fifth Harmony CONFIRMED For Our Summertime Ball 2015!|accessdate=June 6, 2015|date=May 21, 2015}}</ref> and on [[CBBC]]'s ''[[Friday Download]]'' a month later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/cbbc/episode/b0622gpw/friday-download-series-9-episode-12|title=Friday Download - CBBC|publisher=BBC|date=|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}{{expired link|date=September 2016}}</ref> The group performed the song with [[Kid Ink]] for the first time on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live]]'' on June 18, 2015, and this was also their first ever late night appearance.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/41075/20150617/fifth-harmony-kid-ink-jimmy-kimmel-live-worth-it-performance-twitter.htm |title=Fifth Harmony, Kid Ink to Make Late Night Debut on 'Kimmel' with 'Worth It' : Buzz|journal=Music Times|accessdate=2015-09-13}}</ref>\n\nThe group returned to the United States after performing in several programs in the United Kingdom with a morning appearance on ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|The Today Show]]'' along with two other songs from their album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7600000/fifth-harmony-perform-medley-on-today-show-summer-series-watch|title=Fifth Harmony Perform Medley On \u2018Today Show\u2019 Summer Series: Watch|accessdate=July 10, 2015}}</ref> At the [[2015 Premios Juventud]] and the season finale of the Latin American singing competition ''[[La Banda (TV series)|La Banda]]'', the group sang a mix of \"Worth It\" and \"Dame Esta Noche\", the Spanish version of the aforementioned single.<ref name=\"Latin Times\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latintimes.com/pulse/watch-fifth-harmony-slay-worth-it-spanglish-premios-juventud-2015-video-330103|title=Watch Fifth Harmony Slay 'Worth It' In Spanglish At Premios Juventud 2015!|work=Latin Times|date=July 16, 2015|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/6805623/fifth-harmony-one-direction-la-banda|title=Fifth Harmony & One Direction to Appear on 'La Banda' Finale|work=Billboard}}</ref> As one of Taylor Swift's many guest appearances on her [[The 1989 World Tour|1989 World Tour]], the group performed the song with Swift herself in [[Santa Clara, California]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Adams|first=Char|url=http://www.people.com/article/taylor-swift-fifth-harmony-perform-worth-it|title=Taylor Swift Performs With Fifth Harmony on 1989 World Tour|magazine=People|date=August 15, 2015|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref> Other performances included the [[2015 NBPA Players Awards|BET Players' Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|title=The Players' Award: Fifth Harmony and Kid Ink Made It All \u2018Worth It\u2019|url=http://www.bet.com/video/the-players-awards/2015/performances/kid-ink-fifth-harmony.html|website=BET|accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> a red carpet performance at the [[2015 MTV Europe Music Awards]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6738476/fifth-harmony-worth-it-on-mtv-emas-red-carpet-europe-music-awards|title=MTV EMAs 2015: Fifth Harmony Performs \u2018Worth It\u2019 on the Red Carpet|magazine=Billboard|date=October 25, 2015|accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref> and a return to ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live]]'', where the group performed in an outdoor concert series with multiple songs, including \"[[Boss (Fifth Harmony song)|Boss]]\", \"[[Sledgehammer (Fifth Harmony song)|Sledgehammer]]\" and \"[[Work from Home]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Spanos|first1=Brittany|title=Watch Fifth Harmony's Slick 'Work From Home' Performance on 'Kimmel'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/watch-fifth-harmonys-slick-work-from-home-performance-on-kimmel-20160325|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> They also performed the song for the second time at ''The Today Show'' along with \"[[Boss (Fifth Harmony song)|Boss]]\" and two songs from their sophomore studio album, ''7/27''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Murray|first1=Matt|title=Fifth Harmony takes over Today plaza for special Memorial Day performance|url=http://www.today.com/popculture/fifth-harmony-takes-over-today-plaza-special-memorial-day-performance-t95391|website=Today|accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\"Worth It\" is also on the setlist for Fifth Harmony's [[The Reflection Tour|Reflection Tour]] and its summer leg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/kristel/index.ssf/2015/07/fifth_harmonys_summer_reflecti.html|title=Fifth Harmony's 'Summer Reflection' tour gives high-energy performance in Cleveland (photos)|publisher=Cleveland|date=July 18, 2015|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref> The song is also on the setlist for the group's performances at the 2015 New York, New York; Atlanta, Georgia; Chicago, Illinois; and Sunrise, Florida [[Jingle Ball]] concerts. The song is also included on the group's headlining [[The 7/27 Tour]] and [[Fifth Harmony (album)#Tour|PSA Tour]].\n\n== In other media ==\nThe song is featured in the films ''[[Little (film)|Little]]'', ''[[Hotel Transylvania 2]]''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ladzinski|first1=Alyssa|title=Fifth Harmony Unveils Video for 'Hotel Transylvania 2' Track \"I'm In Love With a Monster\"|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/46417/20150827/fifth-harmony-unveils-video-hotel-transylvania-2-track-im-in-love-with-a-monster.htm|website=Music Times|accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> and ''[[How to Be Single]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Songs and music featured in How to Be Single (2016)|url=https://www.tunefind.com/movie/how-to-be-single-2016|website=Tune Find|accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> as well as the television shows ''[[The Mindy Project]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=The Mindy Project Soundtrack - S4E5: Stay-at-Home MILF|url=https://www.tunefind.com/show/the-mindy-project/season-4/25510|website=Tune Find|accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Telenovela (TV series)|Telenovela]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Telenovela Soundtrack - S1E1: Pilot|url=https://www.tunefind.com/show/telenovela/season-1/27417|website=Tune Find|accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Lethal Weapon (TV series)|Lethal Weapon]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Lethal Weapon Soundtrack - S1E5: Spilt Milk|url=https://www.tunefind.com/show/lethal-weapon/season-1/38017|website=Tune Find|accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> and ''[[Mary + Jane]]''. Ths song is also used in a [[PetSmart]] advertisement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ispot.tv/ad/AMbq/petsmart-grooming-im-worth-it-song-by-fifth-harmony|title=PetSmart Grooming TV Spot, 'I'm Worth It' Song by Fifth Harmony|website=iSpot.tv|accessdate=September 19, 2016}}</ref> and a national commercial for [[The Hershey Company|Hershey's]] [[Caramel]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hershey's Caramels TV Commercial, 'Feed Your Fancy' Song by Fifth Harmony|url=https://www.ispot.tv/ad/70DQ/hersheys-caramels-feed-your-fancy-song-by-fifth-harmony|website=iSpot.tv|publisher=Hershey's|accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn Chile, the song was featured several telenovelas including ''[[Matriarcas]]''.\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nRecorded at Westlake Studios ([[Los Angeles]]), Windmark Recording ([[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica]]) and The Hide Out Studios ([[London]])<br>\nMixed at Larrabee Sound Studios ([[North Hollywood, Los Angeles|North Hollywood]])\n{{div col}}\n*[[Camila Cabello]] \u2013 lead vocals\n*Ally Brooke - supporting vocals\n*Dinah Jane - supporting vocals\n*Normani Kordei - lead vocals\n*[[Lauren Jauregui]] - backing harmony vocals\n*[[Kid Ink]] \u2013 guest vocals\n*[[Priscilla Renea]] \u2013 songwriter\n*[[Stargate (production team)|Mikkel Storleer Eriksen]] \u2013 songwriter, producer, all other instruments, recording\n*[[Stargate (production team)|Tor Erik Hermansen]] \u2013 songwriter, producer, all other instruments\n*[[Ori Kaplan]] \u2013 songwriter, co-producer, saxophone\n*Miles Walker \u2013 recording\n*Mike Anderson \u2013 recording\n*[[Jaycen Joshua]] \u2013 mixing\n*Ryan Kaul \u2013 mixing assistant\n*Maddox Chhim \u2013 mixing assistant\n*Tim Blacksmith \u2013 executive producer\n*Danny D \u2013 executive producer\n{{div col end}}\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''Reflection''.<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=Reflection|type=CD liner notes |others=[[Fifth Harmony]] |publisher=[[Epic Records]]/[[Syco Music]]|year=2015}}</ref>\n\n==Track listings==\n*'''Digital download'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/worth-it-feat.-kid-ink-single/id990519087|title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Worth It (feat. Kid Ink) \u2013 Single by Fifth Harmony|accessdate=June 6, 2015}}</ref>\n#\"Worth It\" (featuring Kid Ink) \u2013 3:44\n\n*'''CD single'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.de/Worth-Fifth-Harmony-Feat-Kid/dp/B00W8H78AI/|title=Worth It: Amazon|accessdate=June 6, 2015}}</ref>\n#\"Worth It\" (featuring Kid Ink) \u2013 3:44\n#\"Worth It\" (Non-rap version) \u2013 3:05\n\n*'''Digital download'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/worth-it-dame-esta-noche-feat./id1018370557?l=es|title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Dame Esta Noche (feat. Kid Ink) \u2013 Single by Fifth Harmony|accessdate=July 10, 2015}}</ref>\n#\"Worth It (Dame Esta Noche)\" (featuring Kid Ink) ([[Spain|Spanish]] version) \u2013 3:43\n\n'''\u2022 Digital download'''<ref>{{Citation|title=Worth It - Single por Fifth Harmony|date=2017-05-26|url=https://itunes.apple.com/br/album/worth-it-single/1265172093|language=pt-BR|access-date=2018-09-19}}</ref>\n\n# \"Worth It (Non-rap super clean version) \u2013 3:05\n\n==Charts ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Chart (2015)\n! Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|9<!-- http://www.ariacharts.com.au/chart/singles -->|artist=Fifth Harmony feat. Kid Ink|song=Worth It|